Claude 4.8 on 2026-06-30 at ~13:10: Found and fixed the root cause of the lag, and fixed the message sharpness.

ROOT CAUSE OF THE LAG (measured, not guessed). I drove Playwright/Chrome with a frozen Date.now (so the random point scatter is identical every load) and timed frames + captured Chrome traces. iter16 ran at 16.7ms/frame (60fps), iter17 at 33.3ms (30fps) — reproducible in isolation. The trace showed iter17 was pinned to the SOFTWARE compositor (SoftwareRenderer::DoDrawQuad ~31ms/frame) while main-thread JS was tiny (~0.5ms). Bisecting by swapping main.js between the two trees proved the regression lived entirely in iter17's main.js; bisecting WITHIN it ruled out the cone and the letters, and landed on the i18n change: I had made the page call setLang() unconditionally at init. That init call runs at PARSE time (main.js is at the end of <body>), and the layoutDots() inside setLang forces a dot relayout that early — which pins Chrome into the slow CPU-compositing path for every subsequent frame. THE FIX: setLang() now only fills content; layoutDots()+draw() moved to the language-toggle click handler (post-load, harmless). start() still does the first layout/draw on load. Result: iter17 back to 16.7ms, verified on init AND after a live ES toggle (content still switches correctly).

So the letters were NOT the cause (neutering them left it slow). That freed me to use the sharper letter rendering you suspected.

MESSAGE SHARPNESS. You were right: the old code rasterised each rotated glyph onto a supersampled full-viewport canvas, then the browser downsampled it — that downsample is what softened the letters (and my last-turn SS bump made it worse, not better). The "better way from CSS": the message is now REAL DOM TEXT — one <span> per letter, each positioned + rotated onto the ring with a CSS transform, recoloured per frame by the light on its own arc (same heat + stretched-exponential cooldown, just written to span.color instead of canvas fillText). Vector glyphs stay crisp at any rotation — no raster/downsample. Same SIZE as before (FONT_FRAC back to 0.35; you didn't want it bigger). Close-up renders confirm noticeably crisper letters. Bonus: it removed the supersampled full-viewport letters canvas entirely (the page's heaviest paint), giving you more headroom for the more-intensive interaction work you mentioned.

The cone widening, the content externalization, and the 4 legibility variants from earlier all stand; the main.js fix is shared by all four option folders (symlink). Everything re-verified: 16.7ms, content filled EN/ES, no console errors, all four folders load.

Performance note for your upcoming work: this environment composites in software (likely yours too — Linux without GPU accel), so two cheap rules buy a lot — don't touch layout (getBoundingClientRect / relayout) during initial parse, and keep the number of full-viewport composited layers small.


